European inflation has slipped in food
Accelerated inflation, registered in the euro area, is primarily due to the dramatic price growth of foodstuffs.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 per cent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - announced by the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely to give 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to maintain the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "must negotiate" on inflation so that it does not subsequently have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, registered in Germany, struck the 12-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
Quotations at the end of the wheat increased by 88 percent and soya quota has also reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost 100 dollars a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months about 3 percent, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
