In many hospitals it saves with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, first of all, due to the improper application of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the chief doctor of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
A infection with MRSA has recently been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A victim of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after the infection with MRSA and no significant surgical intervention has been performed since then because of the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10, this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance - said Karolina Böröcz, the head physician of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been recorded safely in hospitals, and there is no information available.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methylline-oxaciline.
One third of humans carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, infections of wounds) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once antibiotics are over-applied or improperly applied, bacteria that usually react well to antibiotics become very resistant bacteria to antibiotics and quickly become infected with inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause severe hospital infections, such as infection of wounds or septicemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with a weakened body, to elderly or to people with little weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - Tibor Nyulasi said - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic Resistant
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff serve them in rubber gloves and masks and there are the antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients hospitalized are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not even possible to prevent infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent the hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, but current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of formation and contamination with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients carrying MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological samples are not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This fact is also due to the fact that these medical examinations are not funded by the National Health Fund.
So most of the cases come out in public light when MRSA infections are already occurring visible in the patient - the head doctor of the department of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union is making strict commitments to the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Antibiotic therapy should be undertaken, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less common in the case of outpatients or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saving with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health care personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, use of rubber gloves and masks is a very important role, but also in this regard considerable shortcomings are experienced in hospitals.
The MRSA is infected by drop-out transmission and direct contact between individuals, but in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, you can also experience - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favorable economic conditions is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are carried out, there are fewer such infections or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of the MRSA infection is an enormous expenditure for the National Sickness Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
It appears that the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
