EUR 400 million for infrastructure
The Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and the Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest for a total of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and the environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, which will be made from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit contract worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The credit contract of EUR 150 million is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the Fourth Line of the Metro.
The agreement was reached that by the time Hungary completes with the EU the details of the Metro financing, they will again discuss the subject whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this will take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the appropriations is in line with the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for maintaining the credit at the disposal of the debtor.
