Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, expert-level meetings will be completed on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries of the world are deliberating on the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Discussions on the particulars of developing and industrialized countries are currently taking place.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to reach the agreement that, compared to the situation in 1990, up to 2020, it decreases by 25 to 40 per cent the emission of greenhouse gases.
Another major theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to provide material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on aid to the developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be headed by a 16-member management board, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac is Profit".
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent to 2020, regardless of whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to commit itself to a reduction of even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatory to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol were committed to decreasing by 5.2 per cent, thus 15 EU Member States committed to achieving 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period 1985-87, which our country will fulfil - notes the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
It is much that is at stake in Bali, since within two years the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its latest report by the IPCC, an international scientific partnership of the United Nations dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and could not prevent an increase of more than 2°C of the average temperature on Earth, which would, according to scientists, have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army Recruited on YouTube
British Army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
The British Air Force (RAD) first took advantage of YouTube services: Special Units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers that have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headsquaters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, both the Ministry of the British Community (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
The air force had originally uploaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the view of the Ministry of Defence, they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda practically costs nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - the BBC told the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - but inevitably they have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans set up a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the highly edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear on the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of the losses, but do not present the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way of recruiting shooting video games, downloadable for free, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly instead of the soldiers.
