Venus climate can give an idea of the Earth's future
Venus could have once been an appropriate place for life, declared scientists yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft showed the planet more like a twin of Earth than had previously been observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets have similar size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus could have had conditions similar to those that made the Earth a habitable planet, now believe scientists.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus to a very different type of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by stormy winds and lightning storms.
The results of the European Space Agency for Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, provide an overview of how the Earth could develop catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the Physics Department of Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, states: "It's clarifying why the climate in Venus is so different from that of Earth, when it's two planets so similar.
"Our new data makes it possible to build a scenario where Venus began as Earth, possibly with a living environment millions of years ago."
