Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most like the Earth, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and rubble in the poles, the same ones that also appear in the winter on the Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that there could be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays run from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of the life of Urey-Miller, the rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the Venus surface there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface are 500°C temperatures, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" twin of the Earth, but he remains a twin," said Russell.
The main goal of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question why Venus, so much like the Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus' research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to researchers' opinion, stress not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had imagined," the ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds the windflows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piconi of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also called sunrise star or evening star orbits around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its 92 bar atmospheric pressure is not much like the Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets, water had become crowded that remained on Earth in the oceans, but in Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While carbon dioxide on Earth had become carbon stones, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
